    <div class="sc-section__body">
      <div class="prose">
        <p>Systems software is the layer where abstractions stop being free. Every added indirection has a price — paid in cycles, cache lines, and sometimes nights. The good news is that you can <em>measure</em> it. The better news is that most of the cost lives in a very small part of the code.</p>

        <h2>Memory hierarchy</h2>
        <p>Modern CPUs are fast. Memory is not. The entire game of systems performance is hiding that gap. An L1 cache hit costs ~4 cycles. A DRAM access costs ~200. If your hot path accesses memory linearly — sequentially, with spatial locality — you pay L1/L2 prices. If it chases pointers across the heap, you pay DRAM prices every time.</p>

        <h3>Slab allocators</h3>
        <p>The kernel uses slab allocation for frequently-allocated same-size objects. A slab is a contiguous chunk of pages carved into equal-sized slots. Free list tracking uses the slot itself as storage — no external bookkeeping.</p>

        <blockquote>The first rule of optimisation: don't. The second: don't yet. The third: profile before you touch anything.</blockquote>

        <h2>Inline elements</h2>
        <p>
          You can use <strong>bold for emphasis</strong>, <em>italic for names and titles</em>,
          and <code>monospace for code references</code> inline.
          Links look like <a href="#">this anchor</a> — accent-coloured, underlined.
          <span set:html={mathInlineSnippet}></span>
        </p>

        <h2>Tables</h2>
        <table>
