            <tr><th>Allocator</th><th>Alloc cost</th><th>Free cost</th><th>Fragmentation</th></tr>
          </thead>
          <tbody>
            <tr><td>Bump</td><td>O(1), ~2 instr</td><td>O(1) bulk only</td><td>None until reset</td></tr>
            <tr><td>Slab</td><td>O(1), pop freelist</td><td>O(1), push freelist</td><td>Internal only</td></tr>
            <tr><td>Buddy</td><td>O(log n)</td><td>O(log n) + coalesce</td><td>Internal + external</td></tr>
            <tr><td>dlmalloc</td><td>O(1) avg</td><td>O(1) avg + coalesce</td><td>Both, bounded</td></tr>
          </tbody>
        </table>

        <h2>Lists</h2>
        <ul>
          <li>Linux <code>mmap(MAP_ANONYMOUS)</code> gives you zeroed pages from the OS</li>
          <li>glibc's <code>malloc</code> uses <code>brk()</code> for small allocations, <code>mmap</code> for large</li>
          <li>Zig's <code>GeneralPurposeAllocator</code> detects double-free and leaks in debug mode</li>
        </ul>

        <ol>
          <li>Profile with <code>perf</code> to find the hot path</li>
          <li>Check cache miss rate — if &gt; 5%, data layout is the problem</li>
          <li>Restructure data for sequential access (AoS → SoA)</li>
          <li>Verify improvement — then stop</li>
        </ol>

        <hr />

        <p>That's the full stack. Everything on this page renders correctly in both light and dark themes, with proper syntax highlighting, math rendering, and diagram support.</p>
